{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527610"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:31:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:31:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14207"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14207"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0,0.86,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102773"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6893"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14207"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85256"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"928"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12734"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32926"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102773"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the Emergency Department with abdominal pain. She speaks Yol\u014bu Matha as her first language and has limited English proficiency. She has a history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension. Her regular medications include metformin and perindopril. On examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 145/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is tender in the right upper quadrant with no guarding or rebound tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Order an abdominal CT scan","Start empiric antibiotics","Arrange for a Yol\u014bu Matha interpreter","Administer intravenous morphine for pain relief","Perform a bedside ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate first step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Earrange for a Yol\u014bu Matha interpreter\u003C/strong\u003E. Effective communication is crucial for accurate diagnosis and treatment, especially in emergency situations. Using an interpreter ensures that the patient can fully express her symptoms and understand the proposed investigations and treatments, leading to better health outcomes and patient satisfaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous morphine\u003C/strong\u003E for pain relief before fully understanding the patient\u0027s symptoms and medical history could potentially mask important clinical signs and is not appropriate as a first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering an abdominal CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E without first obtaining a comprehensive history and ensuring the patient\u0027s understanding and consent would be premature. It\u0027s essential to gather more information about the patient\u0027s symptoms and explain the need for any investigations before proceeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting empiric antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E without a clear diagnosis or understanding of the patient\u0027s full clinical picture could lead to unnecessary treatment and potential complications. It\u0027s important to establish the cause of the abdominal pain first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming a bedside ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E might be a useful diagnostic tool, but it should not precede effective communication with the patient. Understanding the patient\u0027s symptoms and obtaining informed consent are crucial before any examination or procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecognising and respecting Indigenous languages is a key aspect of providing culturally safe healthcare. By arranging for an interpreter, the healthcare provider demonstrates respect for the patient\u0027s cultural identity and ensures that the patient can actively participate in her care. This approach aligns with best practices in Indigenous health care and can help build trust between the patient and the healthcare system. Additionally, it allows for a more accurate and comprehensive assessment of the patient\u0027s condition, potentially leading to a more precise diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recognizing and respecting Indigenous languages is crucial for providing culturally safe healthcare.","Using interpreters for Indigenous language speakers can improve health outcomes and patient satisfaction.","Healthcare providers should be aware of local Indigenous languages and how to access interpreter services."],"references":["Interpreting and Translating Centre - Aboriginal Languages. Government of South Australia. [webpage] 2025. \u003Chttps://translate.sa.gov.au/ALIS#:~:text=We%20interpret%20with%20context%20and,%40sa.gov.au.\u003E","Book an Aboriginal interpreter. Northern Territory Government. [webpage] \u003Chttps://nt.gov.au/community/interpreting-and-translating-services/aboriginal-interpreter-service/book-an-aboriginal-interpreter#:~:text=You%20can%20book%20an%20Aboriginal,(24%2Dhour%20service).\u003E","New South Wales Ministry of Health. (2019, July 1). Communicating positively: A guide to appropriate Aboriginal terminology (GL2019_008). Centre for Aboriginal Health. https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/policies/gl/2019/pdf/GL2019_008.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85256"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14207"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85256"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-15T14:39:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-15T14:40:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6893"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102773"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id